gtr:fundingRef>WT097030AIA</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>081A2D7A-A787-456C-A5BD-BEF9A8EAAB1F</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2011-06-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The findings are having impact beyond the academic sphere in two main ways.

First, results from the project bear on the important issue of whether and when children make &amp;quot;risky&amp;quot; visual-motor decisions. Our studies used carefully designed and rigorously controlled experimental tasks in which no harm can come to participants - however, there are important parallels between the visual-motor decisions children make in our safe lab-based studies, and those in the real world which have important consequences for safety and accident prevention - for example, deciding when it is safe to cross the road. Our research has identified important immaturities in visuo-motor risk-taking late into childhood and we have discussed the implications of these with accident prevention agencies in the UK and Europe - Road Safety GB and Veilig Verkeer Nederland (&amp;quot;Safe Traffic Holland&amp;quot;), who acknowledge that the research highlights important new issues. We are continuing to work with these agencies to identify how the existing research can be used to inform policy, and which kinds of additional approaches (e.g. studies more closely related to natural situations outside the lab) are needed. Accident prevention has societal impact, impact for the economy (in reducing costs due to accidents), and potential implications for changes to policy.

Second, the project involved scientific research with young participants in which they took part in perceptual/motor tasks and/or neuroimaging. We have taken many steps to engage children, schools, and the public in our research. Our activities have included (i) presentations about our research at primary schools, (ii) interacting with the public who are taking part in research at the Science Museum in London, (iii) introducing children who come to the lab to science in a fun and accessible manner via our carefully designed tasks and explanations afterwards, (iv) providing children taking part in neuroimaging with pictures of their brain and other information related to the study, and (v) using these to facilitate school &amp;quot;show and tell&amp;quot; sessions. This approach improves the public understanding of science and encourages interest in scientific education and scientific careers from a young age, with clear benefits to culture, the economy, and society (including social mobility).</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>B0E728E9-BD0B-4952-B136-ABEB22B9C4D1</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal,Economic,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Education,Government, Democracy and Justice,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Overview 

We investigated development of children's abilities to make efficient perceptual and motor judgments. These abilities are crucial in risky everyday activities such as road-crossing. A major innovation in our approach was comparing participants' behavior with quantitative predictions of economic decision-making models. A second innovation was use of model-based brain imaging to ask how areas of visual cortex combine information to make perceptual decisions during childhood. Our characterization of the development of visuo-motor efficiency in childhood is a crucial step towards understanding how children learn efficient solutions to visuo-motor problems, including everyday problems with important safety implications such as road-crossing.

Research highlights

1. In a visuo-motor task participants collected points by touching targets on a screen while avoiding partially overlapping targets that lose points. We used a mathematical model to analyse responses. Adults' distributions found the &amp;quot;optimal&amp;quot; trade-off balancing risks and rewards to maximize points. However, this ability was still developing between 6 and 11 years, and children as old as 11 used overly risky strategies. This result generalizes previous findings of &amp;quot;risky&amp;quot; decision making in childhood to the visuo-motor domain and suggests that the brain's computations with value and probability are immature late into childhood.

2. To characterize development of abilities to take into account the reliability of perceptual information while deciding when to make a motor action, we asked participants to try to point to a hidden target. They had to trade off amount of information about the location (number of clues - dots on the screen) against the reward, as each additional clue lowered its value. Adults chose optimal trade-offs, showing implicit understanding of the precision of the perceptual information provided by the clues (dots). Children aged 6-11 years were near-optimal in some circumstances, but showed &amp;quot;under-sampling&amp;quot; in others, particularly at younger ages. This pattern, analogous to not waiting long enough to collect certain perceptual information ahead of crossing a road, shows another way in which immature computations with probability and reward may underlie &amp;quot;risky&amp;quot; visuo-motor behaviour in childhood.

3. To determine the manner in which mature integration of probabilistic estimates may depend on brain changes, we used a perceptual depth estimation task to compare behavioural abilities with brain activation in 6-13 year olds and adults. We used functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and multi-voxel pattern analysis (MVPA) to measure which visual brain areas were combining motion and binocular disparity information to improve perceptual estimates. Our initial results indicate development both of behavioural abilities and information integration in visual cortex at around 10-11 years. This result directly links perceptual immaturities at making complex probabilistic judgments with development in specific brain areas.

Collaborations and training

During this project we developed collaborations with Prof Laurence Maloney (NYU) and Prof Andrew Welchman (Cambridge) and learnt new methods for mathematical modelling and neuroimaging analysis. These partnerships with international experts from outside the field of child development have strengthened our own research capabilities and will lead to publications enhancing the profile of ESRC-funded psychology research in the UK.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>In the academic domain, the research is of multidisciplinary interest -for child development, as well as for basic aspects of perception, action, decision making and learning. We have communicated our major results at conferences to all of these audiences (see Outputs); our next priority is full publication of the project's findings in international journals with a wide readership. Next, we intend to follow up questions opened up by the research in further UK and international grant proposals. We intend to continue the academic collaborations developed over the course of this project as part of these. The research area as a whole also has great potential for applied impact in the domain of child safety. However, our initial results from controlled laboratory tasks are a long way from providing recommendations to changes in education or policy. We will communicate our initial results to the Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents, the Child Safety Education Coalition and the Department for Transport. We will aim to develop partnerships with these to inform the next stage of our research in such a way that it has the potential to answer applied questions - for example testing interventions that could improve safety.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>0B4BFEC3-BC73-4895-A9FC-C2A3757EBE09</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:r